#  Introduction 
For my final project, I plan to use the Sleep Health and Lifestyle Dataset, a publicly available educational dataset containing information on sleep patterns, lifestyle behaviors, and basic health indicators for 374 individuals. The dataset includes variables such as sleep duration, sleep quality, physical activity level, stress level, BMI category, heart rate, blood pressure, daily steps, and the presence of sleep disorders, along with demographic characteristics like age, gender, and occupation. My R Markdown report will focus on exploratory data analysis to examine relationships between lifestyle factors (e.g., physical activity and stress) and sleep health outcomes, particularly sleep quality and sleep disorders. The report will include data cleaning, descriptive statistics, and visualizations such as histograms, boxplots, and correlation plots, and will be fully reproducible using R code embedded within the document.

# Methods 
he Sleep Health and Lifestyle Dataset was imported into R from a local CSV file. Variable names were standardized using the `clean_names()` function from the janitor package to improve readability and reproducibility. Exploratory data analysis (EDA) was conducted to summarize key variables related to sleep health and lifestyle factors.

Descriptive statistics, including means and frequencies, were calculated for selected variables such as sleep duration, stress level, and physical activity level. Relationships between lifestyle factors and sleep health outcomes were examined using correlation analysis and graphical visualizations, including histograms and boxplots. All analyses were conducted in R using tidyverse packages.



# Results

```{r}
summary_table <- data %>%
  summarise(
    Mean_Age = round(mean(age, na.rm = TRUE), 2),
    Mean_Sleep_Duration = round(mean(sleep_duration, na.rm = TRUE), 2),
    Mean_Stress_Level = round(mean(stress_level, na.rm = TRUE), 2),
    Mean_Daily_Steps = round(mean(daily_steps, na.rm = TRUE), 2)
  )

summary_table %>%
  kable(
    caption = "Table 1. Summary Statistics of Key Variables"
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE, position = "center")

```

```{R}
vars <- data %>%
  select(sleep_duration, quality_of_sleep, physical_activity_level, stress_level)

cor_table <- round(cor(vars, use = "complete.obs"), 2)

knitr::kable(cor_table, caption = "Table 2. Correlations among sleep and lifestyle variables") %>%
  kableExtra::kable_styling(full_width = FALSE, position = "center")
```

Table 1 presents summary statistics for selected variables in the dataset. 
Table 1 shows correlations among key sleep and lifestyle variables. Sleep quality tends to be related to stress level and physical activity level, suggesting potential associations worth exploring further.


```{R}
boxplot(
  stress_level ~ sleep_disorder,
  data = data,
  main = "Figure 1. Stress Level by Sleep Disorder Status",
  xlab = "Sleep Disorder",
  ylab = "Stress Level (1–10)"
)
```

Figure 1 compares stress levels across sleep disorder categories. Differences in medians and variability suggest that stress may vary by sleep disorder status.
Figure 2 displays a boxplot of stress levels (measured on a 1–10 scale) across three sleep disorder categories: insomnia, no sleep disorder, and sleep apnea. The boxplots show the median stress level (horizontal line), the interquartile range (box), and the overall range of values (whiskers) for each group. Participants with insomnia and sleep apnea have higher median stress levels compared to those without a sleep disorder. In contrast, individuals with no sleep disorder show lower median stress and less variability in stress scores. Overall, the figure suggests that stress levels tend to be higher among individuals with sleep disorders.


# Conclusion

This report explored associations between lifestyle factors and sleep health outcomes using descriptive statistics and visualizations. The findings suggest that stress level and physical activity may be related to sleep quality and duration. While this analysis was exploratory and does not establish causality, it provides a useful overview of patterns within the dataset.


